As to the status of liberty the non-free are not ‘persons' and therefore it might seem that they should be passed over. But some mention is necessary (Title 3) of the modes in which men can become slaves; and, again, slaves are capable of becoming ‘persons' by liberation, and therefore the ways in which this can taire place are described (Title 5), and some account is given of the grounds on which manumission is prohibited by positive law (Titles 6 and 7) as also ol restrictions imposed on the powers of masters over their slaves (Title 8). Moreover, the precise effect of manumission had depended on the form of the act, the age of the master and the slave, and the character of the latter; sreedmen had thus not always been of the same kind, and means had been provided to enable them to rise from alower grade in their class to a higher ; but these distinctions, though referred to by Justinian, were abolished by him (Title 5), and the law was thereby much simplilied, though the division os freemen into free· bom (ingenui) and sreedmen (libertini) still remained‚ and had import- ant consequences in the law of successim, which are detuiled in Book iii.
